node.text:
#2019BestNine FILMS! What are your nine favorite films of all time? Here’s my list. All of these films have moved me deeply in one way or another and continue to do so the more I watch them. In alphabetical order:
.
1. Casablanca (1942)
2. The Godfather: Part 1 (1972)
3. Gone with the Wind (1939)
4. It’s a Wonderful Life (1946)
5. La Grande Illusion (1937)
6. Sherlock, Jr. (1924)
7. Singin’ in the Rain (1952)
8. Sunset Blvd (1950)
9. Vertigo (1958)
.
I can’t wait to see your lists! Gentle Reminder: there are no right or wrong lists. And...GO!
Marlene Dietrich kissing a woman in Morocco (1930). This was Dietrich’s first American film and ads for the film proclaimed her “The woman all women want to see!”

Die Hard (1988) was Alan Rickman’s film debut. “Die Hard was a huge event in my life,” he said in 2015. “I walked into a screening in New York anonymous and walked out not anonymous....It was the first film I ever made – I was very ignorant. Nowadays, everyone wants to be in an action or superhero movie, I notice. Then, it was very weird for me to do it....What seems to have been forgotten along the way is that Die Hard has wit and style. That’s why it lasted.”

YAY! Merry Christmas! What movies are you watching today?
Film: It’s A Wonderful Life (1946)
Coming into Christmas like Vera-Ellen in White Christmas (1954). 🎄
Happy Festivus! Tag someone you got a problem with! via @seinfeldtv
Elizabeth Taylor getting in the holiday spirit, 1956.
Dean Martin singing "A Marshmallow World" live on the Christmas special of his TV show (December 19, 1968).
Happy 82nd Birthday, Jane Fonda. What’s your favorite film of hers?
Which one of these wild things from A Charlie Brown Christmas (1965) would you want to party with?
Gene Kelly and Fred Astaire photographed by J.R. Eyerman for LIFE magazine, 1958. Happy Friday!

Eartha Kitt performing “Santa Baby” in New Faces (1954). Eartha later recalled, “it’s that little girl who had the desire to be wicked and kicking up her heels and saying I want this, I want this... She wanted to earn it.” Eartha added, “Every time I sing ‘Santa Baby,’ I laugh more at myself… The song says, ‘Santa Baby, slip a sable under the tree.’ Well, all the men who have done that with me never stayed with me. So I realize everything that I want in life I have to pay for myself, and I really love that because then nobody owns me but me—and my public, of course.”

Betty Grable and the Condos Brothers performing the “You Started Something” number in Moon Over Miami (1941). During her film career Betty set a record of consecutive placement in the Exhibitor’s Poll of top ten box office stars from 1942-1951. Happy Birthday Betty Grable (December 18, 1916 – July 2, 1973).
“When I grow up, I still want to be a director.” Happy 73rd Birthday to Steven Spielberg! What’s your favorite film of his?
Macaulay Culkin lip-synching to The Drifters version of “White Christmas” in Home Alone (1990). His eyes 😂
Cary Grant during production of The Bishop’s Wife (1947). The film was remade in 1996 as The Preacher’s Wife.
Jayne Mansfield decorating her tree. Who’s got their tree up?

Marilyn Monroe filmed by Leo Caloia in 1946 at the Ambassador Hotel. The LA radio station KFI was hosting a talk show about photographic techniques and Marilyn was one of seven models filmed while the techniques were discussed by a panel.
The Nightmare Before Christmas (1993)
“I am a song-and-dance man and I enjoy being myself, which is all I can do.” Happy 94th Birthday, Dick Van Dyke!

“Good morning. My name is Frank Sinatra.” Although he had made brief appearances as a vocalist in earlier films, “Higher and Higher” (1944) marked Frank Sinatra’s acting debut, even though the character he was playing was himself.
Nat King Cole with his daughter Natalie in 1955. Photos via Michael Ochs Archive.

Henry ‘Crip’ Heard lost his right arm and leg when a car in which he was riding in was hit by a train. “The doctors said I would never walk again, but I decided I would be able to dance some day,” he said. “Just remember that you can do anything you want just so long as you set your mind on it.”
Film: Boarding House Blues (1948)
The Supremes (Mary Wilson, Florence Ballard, Diana Ross) in 1965.

Fred Astaire & Rita Hayworth doing “The Shorty George” in You Were Never Lovelier (1942). Rita, who came from a family of dancers, was one of Fred’s favorite partners. “She learned steps faster than anyone I’ve ever known,” Fred recalled. “I’d show her a routine before lunch. She’d be back right after lunch and have it down to perfection. She apparently figured it out  on her mind while she was eating.”
